# Xiaojie — _Design Thinking_
## Critique by Josh Murr
### 21-01-20

Xiaojie is calling for a rethinking of the design pipeline from conception, to design, to outcome. In a world which is currently drastically reconsidering it's relationship with production and consumption she suggests designers should 'take a step back and think about what they are putting out into the world' to confront the role of the designer and their impact in this supply chain. One would be hard pushed to find an industry in the modern world which is not striving for efficiency and "lean-ness" in it's processes and structure as a business.  This analysis in itself could perhaps become suffocating procedure for a small business to undertake which could distract them from their core purpose which, as Xiaojie suggests, is to create meaningful objects.

'Design thinking' is potentially a sciencification of the otherwise abstract concept of design. Wikipedia defines design thinking by what I would consider to be buzzwords which in themselves sum up the Silicon Valley style method of compartmentalising a process down to distributable tasks: __context analysis, problem finding and framing, ideation and solution generating, creative thinking and then sketching and drawing, modelling and prototyping, testing and evaluating__. Surely __problem finding__ and __solution generating__ are a given, and __ideation__ makes me cringe. So I fully appreciate Xiaojie's interjection here asking for more of what she refers to as 'crit'. Whether this is a reference to _critique_ or _critical thinking_, I think either are applicable and necessary in the aforementioned definition of design thinking. I do think however her own comment on this process is what has led others down the path of speculative design where designers situate themselves in a space where they are not driven by appeasing clients, market sales or maintaining image. In fact the process is _driven by_ critical thinking and traditional methods of design ultimately serve to make the more complex ideas palletable. It is all to easy to say 'forget it, critical theory does not lead to sales' and the pessimist in me is screaming just that, but in light of the relentless force of Extiction Rebellion led by todays youth (and at the risk of sound like a naive millenial) I am learning that change is affected on the ground level and we really do need to be the change we want to see.

Xiaojie shows an image of a bright design studio filled with young people sitting at Apple Mac's with desks and shelves full of inspirational hardback books; as a setting it could be an architects office, a graphic design studio or any city-based start up. She is speaking to these designers when she says 'Prove It': prove that you are considering the process in it's entirety rather that rushing to the end goal. She suggests design is in fact a complex process which cannot be 'reduced to 3M Post-Its', which is perhaps another Silicon Valley cliche referenced. It is clear in this however that she is convinced that these methodologies can be brought into the everyday life of the the everyday design team. 

Unfortunately Xiaojie leaves a lot to the imagination in terms of her own work or concrete examples of her vision of a more critical design practice. This leaves these bold and meaningful claims hanging in the air somewhat, but I guess it is up to the designer to see what they make of these ideas and to give them life. It has at least given me the space to digest these ideas and think about how and where they can be applied. Perhaps I am allowing my own understanding of this take off a little bit, but it seems to me that implementing a shift in 'design thinking' is no simple task, and it does raise questions about sustainablity, financial cost and the workplace ecology in doing so. Maybe implementing these practices on a personal day-to-day level will carry through into the more commercial design studio.

As Xiaojie says, 'the world is very messy, and is beautiful'. So I am inclined to agree with her dismissal of 'design thinking' as we currently know it; design thinking is also a messy and beautiful process and has been undermined by the contemporary design studio which has trimmed off anything it can that gets in the way of productivity. But perhaps in doing so the truly thoughtful design thinking has been lost and all we have in its place is cost-effective, efficient, wasteful and boring design.
